%I A393224 #33 Jun 04 2026 18:26:02
%S A393224 140929,121,43,23,53,43691,174763,277,59
%N A393224 a(n) = gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*k) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1), independently of the integer k >= 1 (where p_n denotes the n-th prime number).
%C A393224 By definition of A395171, gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*k) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1) > 1 holds for any integer k >= 1.
%C A393224 Furthermore, gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*k) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1) does not depend on k (i.e., gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*1) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1) = gcd(A395171(n)^(p_n*2) - 1, A395171(n)! - 1) = ...).
%C A393224 Since 700000 < A395171(11), it follows that a(11) >= 700229.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510302/if-gcdn3-1-n-11-must-it-be-equal-to-140929">If gcd(n^3-1, n!-1)>1, must it be equal to 140929?</a>.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/510656/can-gcdnk-pm-1-hspace2mm-n-pm-11-have-arbitrarily-many-but-finitel">Can gcd(n^k +- 1, n! +- 1) > 1 have arbitrarily many but finitely many solutions?</a>.
%H A393224 MathOverflow, <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/q/511242">Answer to: Universal solutions of gcd(n^{p*k}-1, n!-1)>1 for every odd prime p</a>.
%e A393224 a(2) = 140929 since gcd(2283^(3*1) - 1, 2283! - 1) = gcd(2283^(3*2) - 1, 2283! - 1) = ... = 140929 > 1.
%Y A393224 Cf. A000978, A005384, A395115, A395171, A395286, A395944.
%K A393224 nonn,hard,more
%O A393224 2,1
%A A393224 _Marco Ripà_, May 31 2026
